# Command tori

## What does this command do:

Docker server monitoring without the stack. Metrics, logs, and alerts from your terminal. Single binary, zero exposed ports, SSH-only.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/thobiasn/tori-cli/main/deploy/install.sh | sh -s -- --client
For Raspberry Pi install using: curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/thobiasn/tori-cli/main/deploy/install.sh | sh -s -- --client
For Mac install using: curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/thobiasn/tori-cli/main/deploy/install.sh | sh -s -- --client

## Command path

For Fedora run: ~/.local/bin/tori
For Raspberry Pi run: ~/.local/bin/tori
For Mac run: ~/.local/bin/tori

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/thobiasn/tori-cli

## Command options

# Connect to a remote server over SSH
tori user@host

# Connect with a specific SSH identity file
tori user@host -identity ~/.ssh/id_rsa

# Connect on a non-default SSH port
tori user@host -port 2222

# Use a custom client config file
tori -config /path/to/config.toml

# Connect directly to a local agent socket (no SSH)
tori -socket /run/tori/tori.sock

# Run the agent locally (server side)
tori agent

# Run agent with a custom config
tori agent -config /etc/tori/config.toml

# Install agent on server (Linux, systemd)
curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/thobiasn/tori-cli/main/deploy/install.sh | sudo sh

# Client config: add a named server (~/.config/tori/config.toml)
# [servers.prod]
# host = "user@prod.example.com"
